column7: My mom's lesson on standing out
column9:
A ProFellow newsletter from Dr. Vicki Johnson Â â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ â€ŒÂ  Dear readers, Â  Today we celebrate Mother's Day in the U.S. I am sending a note of love to my Mom, and to all other moms, grandmothers, aunties, friends, and caregivers of all types who provide comfort and nurturing to others.Â  When I speak about my MATCH ME FormulaÂ®, the 7 elements of a winning application, I often share that I learned the art of storytelling from my dad, who is an experienced writer and speaker. But it wasn't until I started writing my forthcoming book, _Pitch Your Potential_ [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/Dd82U94vFKrK/xeLlP], that I realized some of the profound lessons that my mom taught me that helped me become a great applicant and career contender. My mom was trained as a nurse, but she stayed home to care for us when my siblings and I were young. Finances were tight. Our family of 5 was supported by my dad's sole salary as a minister at a small church. My mom always had a passion for interior design, antiques, and art history. Although she had very limited resources to purchase decor, she had a defined vision and eye for her decorating style, which I would describe as Victorian-era country living. Our home displayed family heirlooms and wall art, feminine curtains and stenciling, and layered textures in throw pillows, patterned china, and handmade patchwork quilts. There were many vintage items and furniture made from distressed wood and weathered metals that she carefully selected from thrift stores and antique shops. Thanks to my mom, our house was also uncluttered and very clean, which made it comfortable. I remember this because I was the one tasked with cleaning our bathroom for an hour every week as soon as I was old enough to handle a scrub brush! I can now appreciate why.Â  When I was a teenager, I started to notice that my home was quite different from my friendsâ€™ homes because it was more organized and detailed than most. Most of my friendsâ€™ homes held a collection of well-loved furniture and personal things, but without any particular theme. Some friendsâ€™ homes had a more polished look that mirrored a favorite department store, but lacked originality. When I noticed this difference in our homes, it got me thinking about the power of attention to detail and creativity.Â  I have always admired the detail in my mom's selection of colors, textures, and groupings to create beautiful interior designs, and other people did as well. At age 43, she finally pursued and achieved her Bachelor's degree in Art History, receiving the distinction of magna cum laude. She went on to work in boutiques and museums, including Winterthur, a historic DuPont mansion, where she had the chance to apply her skills and eye for design professionally. I realized you can gain positive attention and become memorable when you create something that has high detail, especially when those creations demonstrate that you are paying attention to the desires of your audience. Think of a fancy restaurant or a beautiful wedding you attended. What you notice and enjoy are the small, highly curated details. FROM MY MOM'S EXAMPLE, I LEARNED THAT BEING HIGHLY SPECIFIC - APPLYING HIGH DETAIL IN MY APPLICATIONS - IS A MAGIC INGREDIENT FOR GETTING NOTICED AND BECOMING A TOP CONTENDER. Creating an application that is highly specific doesnâ€™t require a lot of resources. It just requires time, creativity, and the practiced skill of curation. We value something thatâ€™s one-of-a-kind more than something that is common or mass-produced because it's special. Likewise, you make your application special by including specific details in every aspect of your pitch: in your stories, your background and skills, the ideas you propose, and why you desire the opportunity. As the years have unfolded, each effort has seemed more perfunctory and hopeless than the last. Until this week. Late in the night, after we had started printing what was supposed to have been a cover on America’s economy, news broke of the peace agreement between Hamas and Israel in the Egyptian resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh. The ceasefire and the expected release of the hostages are wonderful tidings in themselves. But I was also struck by how the deal opened up new possibilities. Instead of endless, abstract negotiations over maps and the hypothetical constitutional arrangements of two states, the Trump plan promises a practical approach in which Israelis and Palestinians can rebuild their lives. Success looks less like a ceremony in the White House and more like cement mixers spinning in Gaza, as the threat of missiles fades and ordinary people embrace a slowly rising belief in a safer, more prosperous future. It is a triumph for President Donald Trump’s transactional, bullying style of diplomacy. Of course, the obstacles to further progress are immense—how could they not be? Nonetheless, in a region that has known little other than decades of conflict, this is an extraordinary moment: a slender but real chance at a new beginning. That is the case we set out in https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=3a01f9d64b562706d520f5f29ff6f1a776f593e90e4307f14763057236dc25b12ed0a483acb0fd8f3900a96d113a10d1ec676036882e3c76 our cover leader . And it was tested by some of my more sceptical colleagues today, when we recorded the first edition of our new Insider show, free at launch for subscribers to The Economist. I joined Zanny Minton Beddoes, our editor-in-chief, and a panel of editors and correspondents to examine the agreement and consider whether the Middle East really is opening a new chapter. column7: Important: Delta Lake time travel changes - Action may be required
column9:
**

**

****

******

Dear Databricks Customer,

This email requires your attention if you use Delta Lake time travel ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/delta/history#delta-time-travel-syntax ) and run VACUUM ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/sql/language-manual/delta-vacuum#vacuum-a-delta-table ) manually.

*What's Happening*
Starting December 2025, we're updating how time travel and VACUUM work in Delta Lake to make them more predictable and reliable.

*Why This Matters to You*
*Current status:* The period of time you can time travel to depends on when VACUUM is last run, which may be difficult to predict (additional details below in "Details of the Current Behavior" ).

To reduce such risks and provide deterministic behavior, we are implementing important changes to ensure time travel behavior is consistent with file retention settings.

**What's Changing**

Changes How will this improve your experience? Time travel queries will be blocked if querying beyond the delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration. Applies to SELECT, RESTORE, CDC, and CLONE with AS OF syntax. Time travel queries are predictably governed by delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration. The retention argument in the VACUUM command ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/sql/language-manual/delta-vacuum#vacuum-a-delta-table:~:text=options%20specification.-,RETAIN%20num%20HOURS,-The%20retention%20threshold ) will be ignored, with a warning indicating that the value is not used. *Exception:* If the value is set to 0 hours, it will be honored to support removing all history from a Delta table. Simplified experience with delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration as a single configuration that controls what data is vacuumed. delta.logRetentionDuration ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/delta/history#configure-data-retention-for-time-travel-queries ) can only be set greater than or equal to delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/delta/history#configure-data-retention-for-time-travel-queries ). Delta logs are retained for the entire duration that the referenced files are kept to maintain table integrity.

*Action Required*

*1. Check if you use time travel*

* Look for queries with the AS OF syntax. You can use the query history system table ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/admin/system-tables/query-history ) to look for such queries run using SQL warehouses or serverless compute. Example syntax: "select * from system.query.history where lower(statement_text) like '%as of%'"
* If you work with a Databricks account team, they have a list of affected tables we've identified â€” please contact them for details.

*2. Update your table configurations*

* Review and update delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration to match your time travel needs and ensure that the value is smaller than or equal to delta.logRetentionDuration e.g. if you want to time travel back to 40 days, make sure both delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration is set to 40 days and delta.logRetentionDuration is set to 40.

*3. Stop using VACUUM retention arguments*

* Update scripts or workflows to stop relying on the VACUUM command's retention argument. Set delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration appropriately instead to match your time travel needs.

*Timeline*
You will see these changes reflected in your account based on the following schedule:

Table type Using the following compute Date at which behavior change will be introduced UC Managed Delta Tables Databricks Runtime 12.2 and above Starting on Jan 6, 2026 All Delta tables (including UC managed, UC external and all legacy HMS tables) Databricks Runtime 18.0 and above Targeting mid-December, please refer to the release schedule ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/release-notes/runtime#supported-databricks-runtime-lts-releases ) Serverless compute Starting on Jan 13, 2026 DBSQL Starting on Jan 21, 2026

All changes will be reflected in the What's Coming section ( https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/release-notes/whats-coming ) in our documentation.

*Details of the Current Behavior*
To query a previous table version via time travel, you must retain both the log and the data files for that version.

When rows in a table are deleted or updated, the underlying files are not immediately deleted.

* This is to support time travel, which allows you to query past versions of the table. To do so, you can provide a specific table version or timestamp, and Delta Lake can reconstruct the table at that specific version by reading only the data files that were active at that time.

However, when VACUUM runs against a table, the data files corresponding to deleted or modified rows are physically deleted.

* You can use delta.logRetentionDuration to control how long the Delta log and table history are retained (default 30 days).
* You can use delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration to control how long old data files are retained (default 7 days). VACUUM uses this threshold to remove data files no longer referenced by the current table version.

*Currently, Databricks does not enforce or validate* that delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration is set appropriately for time travel needs. This can result in misleading behavior â€” see example below.

Current time travel behavior
This example assumes the default values: 30 days for delta.logRetentionDuration and 7 days for delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration. Time travel behavior after this change *Not running VACUUM* You can time travel up to 30 days, even though you are only guaranteed to time travel up to 7 days. You're guaranteed consistent time travel up to delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration (default 7 days), regardless of your exact cadence of running VACUUM. *Run VACUUM regularly* You can time travel up to at least 7 days + the time since the last VACUUM, as files older than delta.deletedFileRetentionDuration are deleted.

As a result, working with table history can be unpredictable. Time travel queries can succeed or fail depending on your exact cadence of running VACUUM.

To reduce such risks and provide deterministic behavior, we are implementing the above-mentioned updates to ensure time travel behavior is consistent with file retention settings.

If you have any additional questions or concerns, please contact help@databricks.com.

action towards your goals. If youâ€™d like to check it out, hereâ€™s

https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h664rr3hzhwx48666sn/3ohphdu7w8xr7xup/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249MTlGZWJfdG9wbGluZSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bGlmZW5vdGVz
).

Anyway, this week I wanted to share a concept from Oliver
Burkemanâ€™s Meditations for Mortals (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h664rr3hzhwx48666sn/wnh2h6uwzdm4w6sl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL21lZGl0YXRpb25zZm9ybW9ydGFscw==
) that I read a few weeks ago which really resonated. Hereâ€™s the
quote from chapter 15:

The New Age author Julia Rogers Hamrick once wrote a book,
Choosing Easy World, in which she argues itâ€™s as simple as
repeating a mantra: â€˜I choose to live in Easy World, where
everything is easy.â€™ When some daunting challenge barrels into
view, just decide that youâ€™re going to experience it as easy
instead. I realise that sounds like the worst kind of denial of
human limitation, as if you could get your way merely by
commanding the universe to fall in line with your desires. In
fact, though, it can be surprisingly effective â€“ because it
functions not as a mystical command to the universe but as a
reminder to yourself not to fall into the old habit of adding
complications or feelings of unpleasant exertion where neither
need exist.
I havenâ€™t read Hamrickâ€™s Choosing Easy World yet - just bought it
on Kindle. But that mantra that Burkeman quotes â€œI choose to live
in Easy World, where everything is easyâ€ has been living
rent-free in my head for the past few weeks, in a surprisingly
helpful way.

I choose to live in Easy World, where everything is easy.
Over the past couple of weeks, Iâ€™ve found myself noticing various
instances where reminding myself of the mantra has helped. Some
examples

* Iâ€™m working on a new YouTube video and the usual thoughts come
up: â€œargh this content isnâ€™t good enough, it needs more prep, it
needs more science backing it up, argh itâ€™s repetitive, I already
made a video about this 4 years ago arghâ€. Instead of letting
those make the process feel effortful and â€œhardâ€, I remind
myself: â€œI choose to live in Easy World, where everything is
easyâ€. Suddenly, the pressure eases a bit, and I can approach the
video with a lighter heart.
* I wake up in the morning on a weekend, see that itâ€™s 8:30am,
and think â€œargh Iâ€™m still tired, I want to sleep for an extra
hour, but if I do itâ€™ll be 9:30am, and I wonâ€™t get started with
getting stuff done until like 10am, and thereâ€™s so much to do and
not enough time to do itâ€¦..â€. In that moment (which has happened
on a handful of days in the past few weeks), I remind myself: â€œI
choose to live in Easy World where everything is easy.â€ In that
world, would I feel bad about getting an extra hour of sleep? Nah
probably not. Letâ€™s go back to sleep, and maintain the 100% sleep
score.
* Iâ€™m rushing from the gym back home, slightly panicking about
being late, feeling the tension of the lift taking ages to come
down. In that moment, I think: â€œoh yeah, I live in Easy World
where everything is easyâ€. It helps me relax, and realise that I
canâ€™t do much about the lift being slow, and being a few minutes
late to the meeting isnâ€™t that big a deal, so I may as well take
a breath, enjoy the scenery and chill out about it.

The phrase reminds me of Tim Ferrissâ€™s journaling prompt: â€œWhat
would this look like if it were easy?â€ which Iâ€™ve gotten a lot of
value out of over the years. Itâ€™s somewhat similar to the idea I
write about in Feel-Good Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h664rr3hzhwx48666sn/8ghqh3ul48w3lmtl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5mZWVsZ29vZHByb2R1Y3Rpdml0eS5jb20vbGlmZW5vdGVz
) too: â€œWhat would this look like if it were fun?â€

Thereâ€™s something about choosing to live in an easy world that
feels particularly freeing. Itâ€™s a reminder that we donâ€™t have to
make things harder than they need to be, a theme that Burkeman
talks about a lot in Meditations for Mortals and 4,000 Weeks (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h664rr3hzhwx48666sn/m2h7h6u8rx298xfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3I3ZzJV
) too.

So, hereâ€™s a thought experiment for you: What would change about
your life if, just for this week, you decided to adopt this
mindset? Next time youâ€™re struggling with something, try saying
to yourself, I choose to live in easy world where everything is
easy. How might that change your approach? Would it help you to
let go of some of the stress and pressure?

Itâ€™s worth caveating, of course, that your problems are unlikely
to magically disappear by just asking yourself this question. But
like me, I wonder if you might find that it helps you let go,
just a little bit, of the unnecessary extra angst, stress and
suffering, we add on top of whatever â€œproblemâ€ we need to solve.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

If your goal is to start/grow a YouTube channel in 2025, this is the perfect time to sign up. Click here (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWrcPz76ndw6W7wXqJw2fxCCxW4gSXWJ5nYrDNN76MZ_n3pyd0W8wLKSR6lZ3mGW24lkLB2tX5cfW1273w11QY7mcN8Zt-BhXdrk0N3lwqXTsN7bTW4ZDCLd67CT7GN3stL3SD6W86W3r_7G44MD-mpW8G9BlN96P77xW8-XMwF2xbK03W6TYlFX2Wcl_cW3-HFfW7zqB-0N1jYHWdrF3JKW7Zc6mJ8V3NwcW176c2c8yF-m9W7V7s-b2lTPplW5-YJX04_6VZ6W101ds-5Wnl1DN6BnplMgXbVrW41dJ9_2BLgBXW5nF1rf1mW0tTW2HysY35860tjW5HJLz718F0NdVFX1yW1Ps5lKW5_8F7t7bYhHDW4Y777w7plmKjW4PSNPH7_t9c-W31fDx51spP0zW3RBvlg24JN5Nf3NhwRn04 ) to check it out :)

Anyway, this week, I want to talk about habits, morning hydration, and a $5 water bottle :)

We've all heard that drinking water first thing in the morning is super important for energy levels. I've literally made videos about this. I've read the studies. I've nodded along sagely when health experts talk about it. And yet, for years, I've never managed to actually do it consistently.

It's not for lack of trying. I've bought fancy water bottles. I've set reminders. I've tried putting massive bottles by my bed. But nothing stuck. The problem was always the same - I'd wake up, see the giant bottle, think "ugh, that's a lot of water," ignore it, and make a coffee instead (itâ€™s still liquid, right?).

But sometimes the solution to a big problem comes in a small package. In this case, a $5 plastic bottle from Muji (In case youâ€™ve never been, Muji is a Japanese retail store that sells household stuff.)

I bought it randomly while my wife Izzy was shopping for clothes. It's nothing special - just a basic 350ml bottle. I spotted the bottle while Izzy was shopping and thought "that's quite cute."

Here's what's interesting: The small size of the bottle completely changed the game. 350ml is perfect - it's about two glasses of water, which feels substantial enough to make a difference, but not so much that it feels daunting. It's like the Goldilocks of water bottles - not too big, not too small, just right.

My morning hydration system is (maybe embarrassingly) simple:

- Fill bottle before bed
- Wake up
- Actually drink the water (because it doesn't feel impossible)

I've been doing this for a few weeks now, and it's actually having a proper impact on my energy levels. Instead of coffee being the first thing to hit my system each morning, it's water. Given how dehydrated we get during sleep, this makes a lot of sense.

But here's the bigger lesson: Sometimes when we struggle to build a habit, it's not because we lack motivation or discipline. It's because we're making the task itself too daunting. We set ourselves up for failure by trying to drink from metaphorical (and literal, I guess) giant water bottles.

Breaking down your goals into smaller, more manageable chunks isn't just productivity advice - it's actually the difference between building a habit that sticks and another failed attempt at change. Whether it's drinking water, reading books, or learning a new skill, sometimes the key is to make the daily goal small enough that your brain doesn't immediately reject it.

So next time you're struggling to build a new habit, you might like to ask yourself: "Am I trying to drink from too big a bottle?"

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: Understanding the â€œTâ€ in ETL: A Back-to-Basics Guide to Data Transformations
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/understanding-the-t-in-etl-a-back

Over the past year, Iâ€™ve been writing about several back-to-the-basics topics, like extracting data via APIs and SFTP, and building solid data models. But I realized I hadnâ€™t yet touched on the â€œTâ€ in ELT/ETL: transformations.
And thatâ€™s where data and analytics engineers often spend a lot of their time, whether itâ€™s standardizing inputs or layering in business logic.
So in this article, Iâ€™ll break down what transformations are, why they matter, and walk through a few examples.
What is Transform, Anyway?
For a long time, most tools handled extract, transform, and load [ https://substack.com/redirect/47a66d10-28a5-4f5c-ba6a-c706174cf6fa?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] together, no real separation between them. Either that or a developer would manually put together a set of stored procedures that would be run via a cron job and have extracts programmed for APIs [ https://substack.com/redirect/d7d14cb6-f308-4abf-be7a-186bbd683593?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], databases and SFTP.
But what really happens during transform step?
The answer depends on your stack and use case, but at a high level, the T exists to solve a few core problems.
Business Logic - This type of transform is usually focused on rules and definitions that make the data useful to the business. For example it might be used to deal with returns and purchases for a retail company as the data might be in different tables or perhaps returns are only flagged in a field but the actual value of the return is positive. Meaning youâ€™ve got to create a process to accurately calculate the total amount purchased. 
Standardization [ https://substack.com/redirect/6cbb1eb4-596a-4612-abf1-4cf67b8f79dd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - Every system has its own naming conventions, date formats, IDs, and categories. As youâ€™re building your data model, youâ€™ll want to standardize them. In fact, this was one of my first projects at Facebook. It makes it far easier for future users to work with data that has the same set of categories and naming conventions.
Data Integration -One of the major goals of a data warehouse is to provide a way for end-users to join data sets from different sources. That means you might want to join your CRM data to billing and ERP data. But usually there isnâ€™t a magic way to do so. Youâ€™ll have to either integrate systems on the application layer or in the data warehouse. Some where, an ID of sorts will need to be created that lets you join all the information.
Pre-Aggregation - If youâ€™re calculating metrics at scale, itâ€™s often more efficient to pre-aggregate the data. That way when end-users want to query said data, it doesnâ€™t take minutes for the dashboard to load.
How We Used To Handle Transform (And Often Still Do)
Before the rise of modern tooling, transforms were either a homegrown system that engineers built or an out of the box low-code/drag-and-drop tool. Think SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/4d8bbcb6-26ac-4616-9af2-cae9a813d3a9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Hereâ€™s what a homegrown solution might entail.
Stored procedures or SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/75f765db-6d9a-4e3e-98a0-359d53e86fa4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] scripts in your data warehouse
Python [ https://substack.com/redirect/2a57b989-c468-4d9a-a29c-f7ff4b133e45?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or Bash scripts to execute them
Cron jobs, Task Scheduler, SQL Server Agent, Jenkins, pick your scheduler poison
Honestly? Plenty of companies are still running pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/8dac54ba-d5a5-45d8-a7d2-972a5f0ab6c3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] like this today.
And it works, but it often comes with limitations depending on how the engineers set it up. 
For example, you might not have an easy way to integrate your stored procedures with version control. At one of the first companies I worked at we had to both push our code into the repo and then manually change it on the database.
So it was from fluid, and there is a risk that you might push different code to both locations.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
The Rise of Transform-Focused Tools
Enter tools like dbt.
dbt wasnâ€™t the first transform tool, there were plenty of earlier platforms, often with drag-and-drop UIs and some SQL sprinkled in. But itâ€™s hard to deny the fact that many companies have started to use dbt. Especially at start-ups during the MDS boom of the early 2020s.
It stood out because it:
Embraced version control, modular SQL, testing, and documentation
Made SQL-based workflows accessible to a broader set of users
I do want to make sure itâ€™s known that there are other tools such as SQLMesh [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5607bcf-06ba-45d2-bbbf-d7439ce66938?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Dataform [ https://substack.com/redirect/b662aac3-9435-499e-af81-3ad8599388ee?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], so you arenâ€™t limited to just dbt if youâ€™re looking for a SQL based transform tool.
Common Types of Transforms 
Now that weâ€™ve talked about why the transform step matters, letâ€™s look at the what. What do some transforms look like?
To answer that question I have a few examples below.
Value Standardization (Using CASE)
Sometimes, systems use different labels or categories for the same concept, and you need to standardize them into a single value. A quick way to do this is with a CASE statement, this is ok when you have a few categories.
But if youâ€™re dealing with hundreds of values, a lookup table may be the better long-term strategy.
Say different systems record subscription statuses as shown below.
System A: active, cancelled, trial
System B: ACT, CXL, TRIAL_PERIOD
You can standardize them with a CASE statement as shown below.
CASE
WHEN status IN ('active', 'ACT') THEN 'active'
WHEN status IN ('cancelled', 'CXL') THEN 'cancelled'
WHEN status IN ('trial', 'TRIAL_PERIOD') THEN 'trial'
ELSE 'unknown'
END AS standardized_status
This ensures downstream metrics and filters work consistently across dashboards, regardless of the original source format.
Data Type Standardization
Data from APIs or SFTP [ https://substack.com/redirect/6b20c3cf-7d5f-42e6-a01d-bff203471c89?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] might not come in the format weâ€™d like, numbers as strings, dates as text, and booleans as "Yes"/"No" strings.
Thatâ€™s why we will clean that up via standardizing and ensuring all of them match what weâ€™d expect. That way we donâ€™t have five different date formats in our data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/57a447e9-c0b8-478a-8329-0c435b638ea3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
So here is an example of how youâ€™d convert values to a standard format.
SELECT 
CAST(order_total AS NUMERIC) AS order_total, 
CAST(order_date AS DATE) AS order_date, 
LOWER(email) AS email  
FROM raw.orders
Another example would be turning text-based booleans into actual booleans.
CASE 
WHEN is_active = 'Yes' THEN TRUE 
WHEN is_active = 'No' 
THEN FALSE ELSE NULL 
END AS is_active
Categorizing Values For Reporting
Often times for reporting purposes or perhaps segmentation, you might add in categories that are not included in your current data set. For example, in the query below we are marking â€œhigh_valueâ€ customers.
This probably doesnâ€™t exist in your POS, but could be helpful for reporting.
You might also want to create a list of certain customers with attributes for retargeting or special promotions which could also be added in.
WITH recent_spending AS (
  SELECT
    customer_id,
    SUM(order_amount) AS total_spent
  FROM orders
  WHERE order_date >= DATEADD(MONTH, -6, CURRENT_DATE)
  GROUP BY customer_id
)

SELECT
  customer_id,
  total_spent,
  CASE
    WHEN total_spent >= 1000 THEN 'high_value'
    ELSE 'regular'
  END AS customer_segment
FROM recent_spending;
There are still plenty of other transforms but that should give you an idea.
Challenges With The Transformation Step
Even with tooling like dbt, youâ€™ll run into issues. If you're not careful, the "T" layer can end up just as messy as the raw data it was supposed to clean up.
Here are some of the common challenges data teams run into.
3000 Line Queries
Transform models often grow organically. Someone needs a metric, so they tack on another CTE or join. Repeat that a few dozen times, and suddenly, youâ€™re dealing with a 3000-line SQL file [ https://substack.com/redirect/2b7b5a32-f213-4a86-9024-70f9765b4f06?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], 17 CTEs deep, with a bunch of CASE WHEN logic buried in subqueries.
It technically works, but nobody wants to touch it.
Dependency Sprawl
The more models depend on each other, the more fragile things become. Small upstream changes can ripple downstream and break dashboards in ways that arenâ€™t obvious until someone complains.
Without clear lineage or dependency mapping, you risk creating a fragile system thatâ€™s easy to disrupt and hard to fix.
Lack Of Ownership 
In this move fast data world, many different types of data specialists might get involved in creating transforms data engineers, analytics engineers, and even analysts. But who owns the definitions? Whoâ€™s responsible for cleaning up deprecated models? Who gets the final say on business logic?
If you donâ€™t have clear ownership [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd390c98-c7cf-4580-9a72-b315fa2da840?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], in the long-run that speed will bite.
Patterns for Organizing Your Transform Layer
To avoid chaos, your transform logic needs structure. Now when I started in the data world we used â€œrawâ€, â€œstageâ€, â€œprodâ€. Although â€œprodâ€ really wasnâ€™t a great name if youâ€™re also using a dev and prod set-up for deploying code.
Recently, two different approaches essentially co-opted and renamed those layers and youâ€™ve probably come across them either because youâ€™ve worked with dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/11b2c1d1-419c-4a68-b678-1c9c3bd09328?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or read about the medallion architecture.
Just so you have a general idea, here is how the medallion architecture breaks down.
Medallion Architecture
Popularized by Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/9557e144-5af9-4fc9-9139-c1e572bb2627?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], the medallion architecture uses a similar three-layer approach as has been done for a while. I do often find that one of itâ€™s biggest advantages is the naming generally makes it easier for the business to understand what the data team is talking about.
Bronze - Raw or minimally cleaned data from source systems. Equivalent to raw tables where the data is left â€œas-isâ€.
Silver - Standardized and enriched data, sometimes combining multiple bronze sources. â€œThe Silver layer brings the data from different sources into an Enterprise view and enables self-service analytics for ad-hoc reporting, advanced analytics and MLâ€ - Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/9b5c5d46-8039-40d6-99cb-70c592b116b2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Gold - Business-level aggregates and reporting tables, the tables powering dashboards, KPIs, and executive reports or as Databricks puts it â€œconsumption-ready "project-specific" databasesâ€
Other Considerations
As youâ€™re building and running your transform layer, there are a few other key considerations to keep in mind.
Data Quality - Each transform and SQL script is another opportunity to introduce errors. Unit tests  [ https://substack.com/redirect/3d7d19e1-e025-4246-9318-32a633476078?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]and data quality checks [ https://substack.com/redirect/be8c7fc9-4804-4407-ae29-a66b93b48fe2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] arenâ€™t just nice to have, theyâ€™re essential for catching issues before they hit production.
Ownership -Tools like dbt have broadened who can build layers in your data platform, which is great for speed and collaboration, but it also blurs the line of responsibility. Where does ownership of the core data warehouse end, and where do use case-specific layers begin? Without clear boundaries, things can get messy fast.
Developer Experience - How easy is it to safely develop and test changes? I recently ran into a situation where the only way to push updates was straight to production, no staging, no review. That might be fine for a solo project, but in a shared environment with multiple dependencies, itâ€™s a recipe for broken pipelines.
Final Thoughts
Transforms are a critical piece of your data pipeline. Itâ€™s where raw data gets processed, standardized, integrated, and turned into something more accessible to end users like analysts.
Itâ€™s also where business logic gets applied, systems get stitched together, and analysts get the tables they actually want to work with.
Whether youâ€™re building in SQL with dbt, scripting in Python, or using a low-code platform, your transform layer deserves real thought and structure. When done right, it becomes a foundation you can trust.
As always, thanks for reading!

7 Lessons I Learned the Hard Way From 9+ Years as a Data Engineer
Reflection is an essential part of the learning process.
Learning, whether as a data engineer, analyst, or really any position, is not just about cramming as much knowledge into your head as possible; itâ€™s about pausing to consider why certain knowledge matters and how it can be applied. Without that step, knowledge becomes a tool in your workshop that never gets used.
Sure, you can show off that cool tool or share quirky, one-off facts. It might seem impressive, but it doesnâ€™t carry much weight. Taking time to reflect helps you understand where technical knowledge fits and what lessons youâ€™ve genuinely absorbed over the past year, or even the last decade. Where have you made mistakes in picking the wrong data modeling [ https://substack.com/redirect/d472698a-bf01-477e-8aec-f6967f3088f1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] processes or running the wrong project altogether? by Olga Berezovsky

How many dentists are in the world?

- UX consultant Peter Ramsey explores how even well-designed AI featuresâ€”especially those hinged on creative user inputâ€”often fail when users donâ€™t learn how to work with them effectively, leading to low retention or exploration.

- Ramsey emphasizes that onboarding shouldnâ€™t stop once a user performs a single action; continuous guidance is needed so users truly grasp all the featureâ€™s capabilities.

The ghostwriting game is changingâ€¦

And I'm going to help you navigate this new and exciting future for ghostwriters.

But first, some context.

AI is rewriting the rules for writers everywhere.

And savvy clients are ditching order-taking freelancers and desperately seeking writers who can be trusted business consultants.

Which means if you're still using the same old tactics, landing those lucrative, high-ticket ghostwriting gigs is about to get a whole lot tougher.

In fact, by 2026, it might be nearly impossible.

But here's the good news:

Thanks to PGA, we're able to track how the industry is evolving in real time.

We have access to 1,500+ students who're actively trying to land clients and sharing:

â€¢ The objections theyâ€™re getting
â€¢ The questions clients keep asking
â€¢ The new bottlenecks theyâ€™re facing

And now we want to share everything weâ€™re learning with you.

So, Dickie and I put our heads together and decided to host another free, live Masterclass designed to help you land your first (or next) whale of a ghostwriting client in 2026 (or even before the year endsâ€¦ if youâ€™re serious about it!).

Free Masterclass: The 4 Things YouÂ MUSTÂ Do Differently To Land Premium Clients In 2026

I'll be going live on Tuesday, October 28th at 9 AM PST.

And I'll walk through 4 important frameworks you need to understand to land high-ticket clients (which 99% of writers donâ€™t even know exist yet).

Dear friends,

There is significant unmet demand for developers who understand AI. At the same time, because most universities have not yet adapted their curricula to the new reality of programming jobs being much more productive with AI tools, there is also an uptick in unemployment of recent CS graduates.

When I interview (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsT3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3lBW12dp8n37f12FN80Vk1cj-V2pW3zn4m12Z7-v_W1GcZQb7b5J0XW7N9NB54PDcF-W1Sg-f-5w5Q0tW3DX-s_9jWln6W6DgWYM4g86cMW7ZhD723PvgX9VcJL552y1h7ZW4jYqlj8PVCtyF4dcCz7NJcJW8Mgl192sxhNsW5m4P0Z8NbCYlW49HmrL5NclmhW4h4Kdd5Q319MW45kd3n844dqDW3c2f4w3h0jX1W81bh326kVl_gN7TLsvNHyS_mW2QSl_P2gJWmSW1rWHsT4kXnQzW18vmN14qSCvyW4T94MB1Zk1RZW84TyJy5zw8XlW3hdN756ClntpW7LxbM67yc7LZW1XX1ZH3Kv_BBf5-pd5P04 ) AI engineers â€” people skilled at building AI applications â€” I look for people who can:

- Use AI assistance to rapidly engineer software systems

- Use AI building blocks like prompting, RAG, evals, agentic workflows, and machine learning to build applications

- Prototype and iterate rapidly

Someone with these skills can get a massively greater amount done than someone who writes code the way we did in 2022, before the advent of Generative AI. I talk to large businesses every week that would love to hire hundreds or more people with these skills, as well as startups that have great ideas but not enough engineers to build them. As more businesses adopt AI, I expect this talent shortage only to grow! At the same time, recent CS graduates face an increased unemployment rate (e.g., see this study (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsT3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3pJW6-6Nl37T32kLW5dXFJB1Mvq2TW8y-gMl4Hxk83W2x6_yv3cKV2-VCsWxs5JtGdtW2prs5D9j-WhQW6NVR6k1RSpkyW3t_JyN64-Z65W6-YTTz8cWSn0W1371Tq3r7FHxW89fgmF98J9N2W3wT8Fp28GpSfW22-mts4wCwjQW77Xqm111mjM1W71Lr9M8qB6BgW406KxQ7WwfCtW8KlZJ17MZfPNW51WL4S37-0SDW5Th_yr8MVny-W3VSSMt48x7z5W8Cc12P76dxFqN2Wk-sGdXZ7fW7xJ5LB4VlhWGV4P8gR7Tx3P5W8K5Rfx5Jdfh_W18sGfg8Sr42GW1jRLFN3cwJL3W2Y8sqG7ZY_xTf4zCHpF04 ) using data from 2023), though the underemployment rate â€” of graduates doing work that doesnâ€™t require a degree â€” is still lower than for most other majors. This is why we hear simultaneously anecdotes of unemployed CS graduates and also of rising salaries for in-demand AI engineers.

When programming evolved from punchcards to keyboard and terminal, employers continued to hire punchcard programmers for a while. But eventually, all developers had to switch to the new way of coding. AI engineering is similarly creating a huge wave of change.

There is a stereotype of â€œAI Nativeâ€ fresh college graduates who outperform experienced developers. There is some truth to this. Multiple times, I have hired, for full-stack software engineering, a new grad who really knows AI over an experienced developer who still works 2022-style. But the best developers I know arenâ€™t recent graduates (no offense to the fresh grads!). They are experienced developers who have been on top of changes in AI. The most productive programmers today are individuals who deeply understand computers, how to architect software, and how to make complex tradeoffs â€” and who additionally are familiar with cutting-edge AI tools.

Sure, some skills from 2022 are becoming obsolete. For example, a lot of coding syntax that we had to memorize back then is no longer important, since we no longer need to code by hand as much. But even if, say, 30% of CS knowledge is obsolete, the remaining 70% â€” complemented with modern AI knowledge â€” is what makes really productive developers. (Even after punch cards became obsolete, a fundamental understanding of programming was very helpful for typing code into a keyboard.)

Without understanding how computers work, you canâ€™t just â€œvibe codeâ€ your way to greatness. Fundamentals are still important, and for those who additionally understand AI, job opportunities are numerous!

Keep building,

Andrew

Chatbot Interviewers Fill More Jobs

Large language models may have advantages over human recruiters when conducting job interviews, a study shows.

Whatâ€™s new: Researchers at the University of Chicago and Erasmus University Rotterdam found (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsz3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3q3VP5DVy6Y7Y0WW2wXq5z7LfT5hVhvWTz1PwFJRW8dNYwk96Q_plW2fBNPN6zDW2fW5J578x2t9r-wV5SKTs83hq0qN7Ff-XVT1zjzW3HXX021sTtJ4N5lv5xGMphJQW9hr4Mg7rY5zGW8MQCSY25cz3zW5TL3MS8mf0q0W511V5W7Qf2N6W1KGDJs6yjSjbW8c2bHv3LFMSrW6tcCdR7-kHFVW8_8-DD855FBvW8SSBTq4z7HHfW2CDP1h25dLNlN6tSNFLR8RvBW6X13nm6Zm57VW4YCHp45Wh8xlW5r9-0Y6BH7vtW8ZzkXv1P3vPwW2ldbCQ53kG_3f5LRjyY04 ) that, relative to interviews by recruiters, AI-led interviews increased job offers, acceptances, and retention of new employees.

How it works: The authors collected interviews with roughly 67,000 qualified applicants for nearly 50 job openings in a range of industries. The jobs were mostly entry-level, customer-service positions located in the Philippines that offered monthly compensation between $280 and $435. Interviewees were either assigned to the recruiter, assigned to the chatbot, or given a choice between the two. The chatbot was Anna AI (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRr-3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3lXW8FBgS75PcvrmW2D99sY38HMZVW3CcJ7l62LCqjW20fxsZ8tsWLHV1KnPQ2GJY_6N6pxlS9n_qQDW4Tl7PW321YBqW6tX5_l83kT_rW11j1Kj1Fs9kYW7T2Pq-8Lx6HhW426hj66vQZ6YVY_GJZ7qKmtPW7zsf2V69vxJhVkW8B153zRWZW1pqLqg2f2SmxW2qPcWR170RMsN7hPRbRT58CxW7BHMS75zmhpwN4663JVd0_gxN7xqKsW6_wg2W4WDQ7x4HK0CTN1H7NWHwgf7pf2K0kFj04 ) , a large language model with voice input/output from the recruiter PSG Global Solutions.

- All interviews followed the same format: Applicants were asked about career goals, education, and experience and were allowed to ask questions afterward. Both the recruiter and Anna AI were permitted to ask follow-up questions.
- Following the interviews, around 2,700 applicants completed a survey designed to measure their satisfaction with the interview process and general attitudes toward AI.
- Human recruiters made all hiring decisions after assessing interviews via audio recordings, interview transcripts, and standardized test scores. They were instructed to apply the same assessment criteria to each hire regardless of whether the applicant was interviewed by a recruiter or Anna AI.

Results: The authors found that AI can yield more hires, seem more unbiased, and put applicants more at ease than human interviewers.

- Job applicants that were interviewed by Anna AI were 12 percent more likely to be offered a job than those who were interviewed by a recruiter. Among applicants who received an offer, those who had been interviewed by Anna AI were 18 percent more likely to start the job.
- In a free-form survey, applicants interviewed by Anna AI were half as likely to report that the interviewer discriminated against them based on their gender.
- Around 5 percent of AI interviews ended early, and 7 percent had technical difficulties.
- On the other hand, Anna AI covered a median of 9 topics while recruiters covered 5, and applicants interviewed by Anna AI were 71 percent more likely to give a positive assessment of the interview experience.

Behind the news: The rise (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsz3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3ktW3f-sKw37TcSNV599ZH2twgnVW5KNK216fnCwKN4kRnNDLGKdCW752pbJ5YMn8CW5Gzd-m5tNjjcN2Jmz4XHB58WW3YwFdc4B2XvhVg7N505M0fgtVTv56x9cs5XqW7hpvjK81BzQxW8DwXDh9kxnvLW3tK3CB1RF7dqW2s-K0295wG8lVHP-ZC5p15wpW6Ms0By3pc11wW4t0C502dS9kCW8xQXGW8FccyjW80gzQB2Sk_MjW72tZ7x1FJTbjW5BLZ8_477q8FW4Jsv_Y2q6CNZN6-jVwrM-PcdW6XM-CN8k491MW96mrGy165GMTN8-DZRjLWXvGf5pfTSF04 ) of AI software that performs job interviews has raised concerns that such systems may be biased against certain demographic characteristics. Subscribe today (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRrH9bqx4W69v02T6lZ3l9W4z3vc_2LQxTKN14KcFVm9-GrW2Ggnk375ZB2sV2nT2n19SvgrW30QNqR4yVrm4W7g_DkD93j__GW5kkRSy6yVWH6N7WN5Mb_glZXW6lbmVj1Chfg-W3qWP8y2vb9GDW4K__1Y6XJY3tN3BbLkCGVh67N8P_QTVzVfFvW3ld7w61XmkzdW4h91Qc6p9rWhW9bj8yF1KZlKTW82n_lH5Y0MMFW7LryR13JzF7qW9jtgR86MSPLJW63BN-74WD9HqW65GTnB6zl32dW8j94028ZQZNmW8_Hg_87NmTJWW20yWVk4h1hdyW7Rscq92R-mLbW4SXnw56G7TqMW1Z8VGl4-mZLxVSlY1s4jXVZ5N4YwqBtbQlblW392Hsc3WdBqXW214ml46fVN73W3gsXrY47JPhxW4NN1ZJ5CmngtW3WlFz-40K0Q1N7RxrwwK4vQvN4fgRjdjdTSWW1rCsSc4l0qJhV5PFGf6HrYLmW7VwLdm6Zp4sBW8gKsSs3y-ZfVV8Gb168GJFd0W961gjc19cL1dW8qq5wT23TxQ3VZM6dy5nQ5xJW6NK-gb2jZgKVN1CkMLhNn4VwW3z_20x19mkP7W6R52RH4W6G_cW58dVBm23MxP4W4RCMGv79PRxWW90v9wp8gh1L-W8l1PJ94DWZRZW54d2ww5S48p6W1B2fd-5p9bPrW8289gQ8S34KDW4VcbgM16FGc-W3mcNt22BM85QW4jqM0s6ckry-N1y1PM_sF0GlW34KTpN5djGHPW3hXSJG95Cl1qW7nq3Sv5XxH8MW1HJJTw7Lh7B7W39H2Ys92XcY2W2GxHsn4sSj8tW4DpnrM4tQ0PgW5Vk9tf3hdqvYW4r831F5yQxkNf3zTG0404 ) !

Geminiâ€™s Environmental Impact Measured

Google determined that its large language models have a smaller environmental footprint than previous estimates had led it to expect.

Whatâ€™s new: For one year, Google researchers studied (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRr-3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3lLW4ksFsn1ZMCcKW2kzyLy5YYznjW6DJp4k5GnW4dVS1jGH5d0Vm7W6k3-TC1QncB6W8rcpyV6DTkytN7f-vgVcY3bxW96h0qg1vXG96W60VHZ_2D0ZVHW86V-xq2DH0CmW8yfrlD2whJQNW8wgnnr5NCg-PW1vGNnF2GhfG-W1WmP3V2WZlGXW9drnBx2pD914W6_yF5v3-z5LrW8l2NSc46sbSwW5sfzFg9bN38HN28ZQj9c4g-zW1XbZy37HFFh4W9593zc4-c3PzW8xCbS17QS4Nkf6_6pq804 ) the energy consumption, greenhouse gas emissions, and water consumption of the models that drove its Gemini AI assistant in applications like Gmail, Calendar, Drive, Flights, and Maps. (They didnâ€™t identify the specific models involved.) They found that the impact of processing a single prompt was roughly comparable to loading a web page or streaming a brief video to a television screen.

How it works: The authors confined their study to inference in text-processing tasks, calculating the impact of processing a single â€œmedianâ€ prompt (one that consumes the median amount of energy across all prompts and models). They considered only activities under Googleâ€™s operational control, including data-center construction and hardware manufacturing, but not including internet routing or end-user devices.

- Energy: The authors measured energy used to classify prompts, route them to specific models, and rank potential responses. To accomplish this, they traced the hardware used and measured energy consumption of all hardware components within a server rack, including idle machines, active processors, and cooling systems. TPUs, Googleâ€™s custom AI processors, accounted for 58 percent of the total energy consumption.
- Emissions: The authors calculated greenhouse gas emissions by multiplying the energy consumed per median-length prompt by the previous yearâ€™s average emissions per unit of electricity plus operational emissions from sources like heating and air conditioning as well as embodied emissions like hardware manufacturing and transportation, and building the data center itself. They estimated operational and embodied emissions using results from this study (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRr-3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3mRW1yH48S2H0V4sN48KD3yHtxwrW2ns1JZ3mZZXbVr70Sg4Hg9wmW1kFGtG8Gy97HW4LphqQ70tx92N6GFFwM96WQ1W7ZlCt610dhJZW3RDytc3K0-5PW4V-YKj3yTKSnW2b7zXG6KQvH1W3VksFv4pBZbQTx8r11tBqV0W4n2z2b123vZFVBjmHz7sRvd6N5MnYb4l5jcmW68vv6p14GjkZN27qJxx96VKwW3CNxG71ryyhnW3Gs2jQ5MlQXtW6wbmv571CDJZW914bw658JMxNf27DhJg04 ) .
- Water: Water is used to cool data-center hardware, and around 80 percent of it evaporates. The authors measured water input minus water returned in 2023 and 2024. This enabled them to calculate water usage per energy (1.15 liter per kilowatt hour), which they multiplied by the amount of energy used per prompt to calculate the water usage per prompt.

Results: The energy and water consumed and greenhouse gases emitted by Gemini AI assistantâ€™s models fell well below Googleâ€™s estimates in previous years. Moreover, between May 2024 and May 2025, given a median prompt, the modelsâ€™ energy consumption fell by a factor of 33 and their greenhouse gas emissions fell by a factor of 44, reductions attributable to clean-energy procurement and more energy-efficient hardware and software.

- A median text prompt consumed approximately 0.24 watt-hours, around the amount of energy that a television screen consumes over 9 seconds.
- The median prompt consumed 0.26 milliliters of water, about five drops.
- Each median prompt generated about 0.03 grams of greenhouse gases, roughly the amount emitted when loading a single webpage.

Behind the news: Recently, Mistral assessed (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRrn5m_5PW5BWr2F6lZ3kFW7MJw7Y4tb4XvW38QMCn8rSX6jW3YH56P5bgKCFVCbpsg9cycG5W5y-9s866lsmwW8WLS5P3z5Wm7W2wMl097wGBb9N4pFgQfq6N4gV5Djpx4p3HqcW5J0bHk75sn-QW8Rwy6j5ydw2WW1pqs7V88jKlGW4wbNQT3r-fgfW74Yr_W4yjfQ1VlMVtf88t81tW5YnLdr4jwfLnW8TgCcp1-_lKFW93jml07hDPWLW65-3FZ6lc7HhW716ZqF2Wk9n4W399mFg1FFzf4W1ZCljX6WF4D5W82RhPh2rnDfhMvC9G7mt3W5W8vcS0n41z_tWW4TKCvW5-4gbhW6LX3vW6pMZQ-W2h-gdF8BtHQ6Vj81cx2kDynwVp85cT4VWPSPN494HjYHnQ8lW7424G11xsgm9W4vPSgB7H0jnRN7VW3rjnpk9Qf88NKCj04 ) its Mistral Large 2 model in a similar way (although its study included training). It found that, at inference, 400-token prompt generated 1.14 grams of greenhouse gases and consumed 45 milliliters of water.

Yes, but: Earlier research arrived at measurements as much as two orders of magnitude higher than Googleâ€™s, largely because they included factors that Google did not, The Verge reported (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsT3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3mDW4_tc1p1w-BjLW4SDkJ31q8ZdLN8vnRlWxh59PVHqXVN421vS4W8dsCWp4D_fHXW4dP_Hq4-WhMbW52XZhJ5K3Q3NW895g_C9ckMXnW4LZ2Dj2wzmknW3fvXLX6vzfBSW1vXjHX2MGq2_VgHHH874zvJWW76fBs_4qG5HJW5G7p_M7SsSWrMWcCCPPrXQRVBK6XK8FQwDXW38VYmS57kTKDW67sMbP5tTrnHW8fbx4Z1kLrs8W4xKDVZ6LkkVPVKbF821gtDVLW5D0-_r7tbYjVN2mdv9ln0S5GN37m-dWTjNVgW3Z0D0l37L6dGW27wz639b3VPBW4NMfL38P1-SJW8sBDl04ktzRrf7yzQg004 ) . For instance, a 2023 study found that GPT-3 used about 10 milliliters to 50 milliliters of water per (average) prompt â€” greater than Googleâ€™s Gemini findings by 40 to 200 times. That study included water used in generating electricity, such as steam used to turn turbines or water used to cool nuclear generators, which Google omitted. Further, the 2023 study based its estimate of greenhouse gas emissions on actual emissions of local grids, while Google based its measurement on the companyâ€™s commitments to buy energy from low-carbon sources. Google did not respond to questions from The Verge.

Why it matters: Assessing the environmental cost of AI has proven to be difficult, and different approaches paint very different pictures. Googleâ€™s approach has the benefit of focusing on variables under its control and addressing energy, greenhouse gases, and water. However, it leaves out important contributors to these measures â€” including training â€” as well as consumption of materials, as highlighted in Mistralâ€™s assessment.

Weâ€™re thinking: The AI industry needs a standard method that would enable AI companies to report their modelsâ€™ environmental impacts and the public to compare them. Kudos to Google, Mistral, and the independent researchers for proposing practical approaches and continuing to refine them.

Cybersecurity for Agents

column1: Autonomous agents built on large language models introduce distinct security concerns. Researchers designed a system to protect agents from common vulnerabilities.

Whatâ€™s new: Sahana Chennabasappa and colleagues at Meta released LlamaFirewall (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRr-3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3lTW6XsKyj2qm90gW6tFTMV7n8WfYW5V9ky_8yPHqqW5bN7kl3zj7XpW6jPQDL8fs0KDW8j0Qbd7Nn-C_W7zjpZ02DzPB2W4F29jV7gDWZhW3mVhv26MTN-2W8J0K6f4ZNl7mN5N4p_WkXNskW7SshRP8NM8yxW3R1tQv9kd2m0W8g5xkY8C3GfvN4q2VwtpRG-5W4HcNfk7X8jsYVH31w66_TX_vW1WQykb6y4YRbW3yBv7w2pwDj2W5xTSdx2Sx77GVJ8wPm51wg4qW4k5-xz6bdFKcf4bpk6004 )
column2: an open-source system designed to mitigate three lines of attack: (i) jailbreaking (prompts that bypass an LLMâ€™s built-in safeguards)
column3: (ii) goal hijacking (inputs that aim to change an LLMâ€™s prompted goal)
column4: and (iii) exploiting vulnerabilities in generated code. The code and models are freely available (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MVx81C5tk9wW7kLz6Y13QyKHW56dvtZ5C0JTPN1vWRsz3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mDVNGtgH9lGVkBN5G9zMqyNhQKW4-rc2T9kT1mlN2300sdDFyp_W3dLPKy4V1-frW51zC9213HrT9W4dMSpn533Lq1W230N6C70tsZZW6BL5lb1hMF7VW8bd5vF5Cg8JWW3b2GBm2zBcsBW1pXtz81_5qgbVTYzrG8w5bLnW84MYVL7KpRnZW3ssg0k5bq6BhMQW5XndztSQW5yQrfS63RbR7W3q-bld8C4Kt_W7K9MsR2DBhRqVmsg3-6118PtN8NRfjFyYyKSW8nfDGg7ZvNq8W7HP2PW4PHwktW8wyZ-m4K4TDKW2BwNwF5ChGSpW4hccfh2k4Hpgf40tMz-04 )  for projects that have up to 700 million monthly active users.

column1: Key insight: Security for LLMs typically focuses on filtering inputs and fine-tuning outputs. But agentic LLMs retain vulnerabilities that arenâ€™t addressed by those techniques and present new ones as well. Receiving instructions exposes them to jailbreaking
column2: tool use makes them vulnerable to goal hijacking (for instance
column3: when an agent conducts a web search and encounters malicious data)
column4: and output code may open security holes outside the agent itself. To defend against these weaknesses
column5: a security system can filter malicious prompts
column6: monitor chains of thought for deviations from prompted goals
column7: and check generated code for flaws.

Hi there!

Everything you do in PyCharm lives inside of a project <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVkX_XFt39WVWNXvjK-k_bej40L1HGnrjrf4kCrG6L_rajNWpcuHmv7oAIOn4N3fD-RWxtKCjergGFxsi4MfPGO74aGpHZLIGgZg1Y7-kA7dUFEluQic_OLaAeUUzFWau4vcifJX2zPYk-eDQitYw30X/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>.

Projects allow the IDE to understand your files and their relationships to provide best-in-class code completion, project-wide refactorings, and more.
Create a New Project
Select a pure Python <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVnBKTUPNd4m0zgRbIdqVj-Kf2eLKj2Vg2YG8fr9u5MWgN2uM7b3sNR4ea-D-ls0YQTfoPA7bgEUVNXLXXp953sAB3z6uUjAlPYl4WwnxMjqQqNO44P_ZtxV_fWf6-PlWT1I283XZln9H1kZoRc2P_Un/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>, web-framework-based <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVlD49vwsIwOM97qEvocsSDhL3CCOreBeEB1HyxDxm4kycSOInWFBrREjDEO-F3foP3wJrQ8WJX2daCkD65kdxUHniXHnuNszC3YzC5bisN8Pai5H5wh0otrE3f8XA5Ev6ucP9MV7dbSQ9zOishZeuOg/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>, or scientific <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVmkcZ2N7AhgQ5guJgsjDkfll8b4Ucjj1ZBmvmMqECAbs-uTlsG4jIycrsFCrD-SKNwFiY4rF76ldY1anyFdsWq_vU7kTG987ypxd9BqZ8RCTIDs8jLfynEDWmOja_LtKk6SqNWQCUtfvhOSl8o4sAtE/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=> project type, create a new <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVkntgwPqKFFw21gH8xvrllvVtajipzl10Xzq3rYsZEbSLtB_c7G1S81uHIItEBBR_ACHUo2qzzK3Uod8ab5Y0ekBLyVUqvWE_HQw3u3upgnQ9YsqDN5DPIDLBfmUrbR9F2vRGrHBAkCQENiSBCLuotrYIdZZGlRN2AJt1D0Kd1Ak2XQdW5Zlmvpd4BjobL1TVrCiX7kEP4O4AaMJfCJVCKH/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=> or select an existing <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVkntgwPqKFFw21gH8xvrllvVtajipzl10Xzq3rYsZEbSLtB_c7G1S81uHIItEBBR_ACHUo2qzzK3Uod8ab5Y0ekBLyVUqvWE_HQw3u3upgnQ9YsqDN5DPIDLBfmUrbR9F2vRGrHBAkCQENiSBCLuotra0xsbkHM6z3OvQwsF-pOkczbyO60NPU5-RfPHa7RS0w=/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=> Python interpreter, and let PyCharm install dependencies, configure specific support, and create run configurations for you.

Add a Remote Python Interpreter
Remote interpreters can be added afterward through PyCharmâ€™s support for WSL <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVmewHksB55DsnsiV-WkNVUhwrD4XZ0y4vMzXRrnC9RYxmfMLqlhTFC3FcauDuvrvlol6D8sHZUiU6nWUpTX3qQNL7fVrvYDspP6Bra8C-Ex-ZgKHAZjJRZG5QMUfVcjoTn7sJsU40KeqZcEqALsu0A7HtuHpWKSRF9s3oTYa2_kJw==/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>, Docker <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVm7DVqvFzMrg8hDOyByxEMuhSuJiM17ICfl_7ZV4BlILgyrZUV0uGRRtxIlS6xgTQE7AJ1kI-WU64xhnX01gqnq6s3KPTkmS833v8DH5ziQJphz9sNc9ixaK-LyuwJ77XVYTnw5EMkaKduQX9LZQabv5pmc5C608vBXgW6BivSb4g==/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>, and SSH <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVkntgwPqKFFw21gH8xvrllvkKZvl3DYqT9C-QvLaRc-LXBl4B1YlFEI45IO2HARalVg3AoaVGbryf6yJ0oB0wiOqLvpX7XhCr4ZDkdVRcz0lX6TirLG8ScvYrQMw-88S4Pw2S8G1pwYY0yvLbzYhfgtAJqs4QTQMEUBmNC3iiVVBw==/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>.
Run a File
Right-click inside the editor and select Run <file name> to quickly run a file in PyCharm <https://go.jetbrains.com/dc/k2oLQLl4sOXaMfj4PBQzO0xwp2dQmblqwCsEpQn-sVk9o_sqVc_IADP_5XrCvvBcO8GUvYqX32VCoMa_KTSqCy6YAFNVHmkQdAalrvLO2H-wvc1ExXtKgKaeI0hBTbMwWzZTrHXxKVrIg_CLSDDAy4ySGbYBl-Lc227b8JqEH_RBAtuu9_J8axH4efD2OKMZW2TJFW0rRjsOg7iZG83lxw==/NDI2LVFWRC0xMTQAAAGX9o0FrnPk2N4UE63Hp7qSuMrSOIA-JUM78ZUdCgFh3RjB48NugNHQplS_TyoltpBLOP4RmU4=>.

column7: Are labels holding you back? ðŸ¤”
column9:
Hey friends,

Firstly, thank you for the wonderful feedback on the LifeNotes rebrand - we had 250+ replies to last weekâ€™s issue, mostly saying very positive things ðŸ˜Š

This week, I wanted to share some insights I had from a coaching conversation with Danny Miranda (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VW38g_71Md0DN3bRz5BHddc2W7CpFKy5hYnyMN2bpc1H3pyd0W95jsWP6lZ3nZW6JgMSh28_H3MN3jbkyRdBHyKW3vCQfp3VV9PmW5NWNf_7wn3L1W1D8d8R7FgDF2W2HBtHT2jLx_fW4fNmGb1VPQYPVvNJnB87tBylW1GSCP_27BCzVN6q3_wYYPBGyW6yLGGY1hyNW9W5G8HwL4f9FRRN8DnWsZdjxmgW1QkMYv54DFsWW7spVqn8T5rysW52hG5G5qjknGW6SjRQx5_gh1BW7C0YzS2QDQWXV4qFkN1jwvz3W5KNDpc5WBsyXW3rpn124kk1YMN2H_Wflz-NJfW5PWsHT8-KHW6W5qN-VB97NfPhW59DRlr53K4hVW8C2djr8DyLzcW7wNs488VZLG_W8PvmBz4H43ZKW6QnXty1573CHW5m6pd-1XtBWRf1NZ0t204 ) . Danny and I connected a few years ago when he interviewed me on his podcast, and weâ€™ve hung out IRL a few times since. A few months ago, I saw Danny tweet out that he was starting a coaching programme, and because the conversations Iâ€™ve had with Danny have always felt quite transformative, I signed myself up.

Our first session tackled some private stuff, maybe Iâ€™ll share that at some point. But we had our second session this week, and I wanted to share my LifeNotes from the session.

The conversation started with Danny asking me about any areas in my life where I wasn't feeling a sense of equanimity. I mentioned that I'd been feeling a bit lost when it comes to the business - questioning the point of making videos, feeling like they can be a bit repetitive: after all, thereâ€™s only so much advice I can feasibly give about how to stay more focused before it becomes same-y.

This isn't a new feeling for me. It comes up about once a quarter, and I've gotten used to it after seven years in the game. But this time, the conversation with Danny took an interesting turn.

We started exploring what truly motivates me, and I had a bit of an epiphany. For years, I've been holding to this identity of wanting to be a â€˜teacher'. Not in the traditional school-sense of course, but more in the sense of wanting to share ideas that people can apply to help build a life they love. I landed on the â€˜teacherâ€™ identity after asking myself the question: â€œWhat would I want written on my gravestone?â€. For years, my answer has been â€œsomething along the lines of *good father, good husband, inspirational teacherâ€*.

But as Danny and I dug deeper into this idea, I started to realise something: while teaching is certainly a part of what I do and enjoy, it doesn't fully capture what drives me. There's something broader, something more fundamental that gets me excited to wake up each morning.

That something is creation.

When I think about the aspects of my work that truly light me up, it's not just about teaching knowledge or skills. It's about bringing new things into existence. Whether that's a video, a course, a book, or even a new business idea - the common thread is creation.

This might sound obvious, but as I thought about the shift in identity from â€œteacherâ€ to â€œcreatorâ€, it felt pretty profound. When I see myself primarily as a teacher, I feel this constant pressure to have new lessons to share, new frameworks, or principles, or ideas to share in videos, emails, podcasts, books. If my main role is â€œteacherâ€, then either I keep coming up with new stuff to teach, or I â€œteachâ€ the same stuff again and again, which feels repetitive.

But when I reframe my role as a â€œcreatorâ€ instead, suddenly the world opens up. Creating encompasses so much more than just teaching. It includes building new products, designing websites, coming up with businesses ideas, even things like revamping our existing product offerings. All of these activities are (a) really fun for me, and (b) still align with my goal of helping people build lives they love, but they do it in a broader way.

This realisation was liberating. It helped me understand why I sometimes feel demotivated about making repetitive content, but get really excited about projects like revamping our Part-Time YouTuber Academy, or building up Productivity Lab, or developing new software tools like VoicePal. Itâ€™s not just about teaching anymore - itâ€™s about creating something new, something that didnâ€™t exist before.

Reflecting on the conversation with Danny got me thinking about the labels we give ourselves and how they can sometimes box us in. Whether you think of yourself as a teacher, a doctor, an accountant, or whatever - it might be worth stopping every now and then to ask yourself: "Is this label still serving me? Or is there a broader way I could think about what I do?"

Of course, Iâ€™d love to get to the point where Iâ€™m so enlightened that I donâ€™t attach my identity to any labels at allâ€¦ if anyone has any tips on how to get there, my replies are open ðŸ˜‰

Ultimately, this shift from 'teacher' to 'creator' doesn't change my ultimate goal. I still want to help people build lives they love. I still want to be remembered as someone who inspired others. But now, I see many more paths to achieving that goal.

So if youâ€™re up for it, here's a challenge Iâ€™d love for you to try this week: take a moment to reflect on the labels you've given yourself. Are they still accurate? Are they serving you? Or could broadening your perspective potentially unlock new levels of creativity and fulfilment? Iâ€™d love to hear what you come up with ðŸ˜Š

Have a great week!

Ali xx

ðŸŽ¥ My Free Guide To Starting A YouTube Channel (In 7 Days)

One of my favourite things about running this newsletter is reading the email responses you guys send in each week.

Got BDE?âš¡ï¸
Hi BDEs! Welcome to Lessons 0 & 1 of the free Big SQL Energy Beginner Courseâš¡ï¸ Today weâ€™re getting setup and learning the super basics of writing our first SQL query!
If youâ€™re new here, Iâ€™m Jess Ramos, the founder of Big Data Energy and the creator of the BEST SQL course and community: Big SQL Energyâš¡ï¸. Check me out on socials: ðŸ”—LinkedIn [ https://substack.com/redirect/2bf66272-3ab1-4744-b60b-59cbd7081dc0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], ðŸ”—Instagram [ https://substack.com/redirect/6ce691ce-c40a-4a0b-8d21-48acaa29c73e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], ðŸ”—YouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/aeef0cb2-ace1-45f9-bf0f-1472d1a6843b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and ðŸ”—TikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/761b2f65-781e-4bf3-9df6-e0977427e2b0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Big SQL Energy Intermediate is an intermediate SQL course designed to solve real business problems hands-on using realistic data and a modern tech stack. Youâ€™ll walk away with 2 SQL portfolio projects, portfolio building guidance, access to the Big Data Energy Discord community, and lots of confidence for you upcoming coding interviews. This course is all of the most important things Iâ€™ve learned on the job as a Senior Data Analyst in tech who grew from a $72K salary to over $150K salary. And now Iâ€™m sharing it with YOU!
                                  Use code Jan2025 for 20% off for all of January!
But if youâ€™re here for the free BEGINNER Big SQL Energy course, the next lesson for you is below! â¬‡ï¸
Lesson 0: Intro & Getting Started
ðŸŽ¥ Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd1d8b45-fa8d-41f6-ba73-6afb7af7df5b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Before you start, youâ€™ll need access to any IDE (integrated development environment) for SQL of your choosing. I highly recommend using a ðŸ”—Hex data science notebook [ https://substack.com/redirect/43dcc026-9077-4832-90f9-cd3f1daa0399?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] because itâ€™s easy to get started with and stored in the cloudâ€” so no headaches to download and set up. However, you can alternatively use DBeaver, MySQL Workbench, SSMS, or any others if youâ€™d prefer. Just import the dataset used in the lesson, and youâ€™re ready to go! Remember, if you get stuck or experience errors, ChatGPT and Gemini are great resources to learn about syntax and help you debug. Alright, letâ€™s get started!
ðŸ”— Join Hex Data Science Notebooks: https://app.hex.tech/signup/big-data-energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/43dcc026-9077-4832-90f9-cd3f1daa0399?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
ðŸ”— Datasets (Orders & Customers): https://github.com/jessramosdata/big-sql-energy-beginner [ https://substack.com/redirect/e7176d16-b911-47f8-adad-985a7052253f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Lesson 2: Order By
ðŸŽ¥ Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/6490f39c-bc1d-46ce-bb8b-de659e23d289?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Now that youâ€™ve learned how to pull some data using SELECT and FROM combined with * or column names, I bet youâ€™re wondering how to sort data in SQL. It can be really hard to see any trends or insights with a large amounts of data, so sometimes we have to summarize, rearrange, or reshape data in order to learn more. However, I do want to caution you that sorting an entire dataset can have negative impacts to optimization since it can take a lot of time and power to sort a very large dataset. But letâ€™s ignore that for now since weâ€™re learning the basicsâ€” I talk more about optimization in my ðŸ”—intermediate course [ https://substack.com/redirect/e22e252f-8387-46d3-90e3-6763ad5f8158?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
To sort a dataset in SQL, we have to use the ORDER BY clause in SQL. By default, ORDER BY sorts in ascending order, or in other words smallest to largest. We can add it after FROM like this:
select
   *
from
   table
order by
   order_date
There are other SQL clauses that sometimes go between FROM and ORDER BY, but weâ€™ll learn those later. If you want to switch the order to descending order (largest to smallest), you can do it by adding â€œdescâ€ after the column name:
select
   *
from
   table
order by
   order_date desc
And of course you can order by multiple columns as well too. Itâ€™ll order by the first column and then by the second column. Hereâ€™s a few examples of that. Notice how including desc and changing the position changes our ordering:
select
   *
from
   table
order by
   customer_id, order_date
;


select
   *
from
   table
order by
   customer_id, order_date desc
;

select
   *
from
   table
order by
   customer_id desc, order_date
;

select
   *
from
   table
order by
   customer_id desc, order_date desc
;
In some SQL dialects (especially in newer cloud platforms like Snowflake for example), you can use a shorthand notation to represent the column name based on the columns selected in the SELECT statement. Order by 1, 2 orders by the first and second column in your select statement for example:
select
   *
from
   table
order by
   1, 2
;
And thatâ€™s how we can sort datasets in SQL! See you tomorrow for the next lesson!
